TextBlock.TextLine: Adij 15 maij 1697
brussel guilliam walravens
ick hebbe ul briven van 4 & 13 deser wel ontfangen hijt den eersten
sent gij mij wederom het laken No. 311 a ƒ3:4 seggende het laken
gaet wel geconditioneert terugh en is niet open gedaen geweest, dat
mach ul seggen aen die het niet verstaen maer aen mij niet want
het toillet is afgeweest ende netto weder averkeert aen gedaen de coord
altemael los & geheel gedelivalikers patientie sal meer als die prijs
even wel gelden, en hebbe meer dan een hiere besigh geweest omtus
eenichsins te erstellen, ul ordoneert mij te trecken ƒ 483, in plaetve
ƒ 486:11, gij maeckt altijdt pretentien om te corten, buijten thwijffel
seijsende het gene men corten can eersst betaelt is, maer dat magh
soo niet gaen nu op hope van meerder gelt van ul te hebben soo trecke
ick ƒ 484:want ul en considereert de st. 11 niet sulckx dat ick ul
toen staen op st:9 naer wat gij begeert sijnde het bewijs gestelt
in voldoninge. onse convaijen sijn gearriveert, doch de goederen
sullen soo haest noch niet hier wesen, en apparent noch wel 14
daegen aen loopen sal ul van alles kennisse geven. ter wijlen blijve.
th
London messr. Kent
16 ditto
in answer to yours of 20 & 30 past, the convoijes are also well
arrived in holland when boath the english & hath will give such
convoij, then wee may tiade fteley, butt god knoulves, when
Thael
raad
sijck de convoij bee granted aghine ruyest hope one from London
for ostend, before I gust & one about october what orders you have
from mee must come by e first convoij, for I shall send en other
memorandum for the second convoij for the gods arrived with
these shall bee soon gone, therefore pray accordinley & take forme
all the advantage you kan & gelaye ot bainge, if you suppore
e neeu woll will couse the prise oft fall. I take notice what you
said of the cotton of chered 4 februatij last, this my mistake & you
are in the right, keept that bale for mij accompt, to bee shipped
bijdte first convoij for ostend beside the 3 bales, noted in the
memorandiem, so that these will bee 4 bales of cottons, & ck
please to buy when you iuadge best as to the ex. wee must have
patience, all my remites shall bee made af you dirrest, as inclosed
s £350:- en S. theodor Janssen for ABh procure the needful, cest
me 35:7 is a great ex. hath itt not been upon exspectatson of a
fall, I should have remitted manney £100 att 35, now I will go
trough, for I will not have you draw on mee principalley, because sha
seen your bill on the widdow de bie 30 the march 2 uso att 36 for
Edward hast well when on the lameday you draw on mee for the same my
att one uso att 36:1, so the hath one is cheaper because her bill is
one month longer, please to make the nomber of sp. clothes from 50
to 54 p. up to 60, to the n° 11 „ 13 „14 „ 18 „ 21 & 23, the lowelf that
are to bee had, for the seems, the costi coull: & copperrose will bee
the most demanded for winter with the lowelcy draps as N.6„8
20 or 24 no may beedarker of the browns at the patt. sent rather
some what lighter as w1„ 3 „5 & 9, to you gouverno itt beinge the needfull
att present from.
Adij 16 maij 1697
leds thomas potter
ichrenomy last to you was 6t court wh I suppose reached y . handes ditto, becau
mes jour letters of 6t are answered from london, non have before mee yours of
psse them
toram 23 past, by wh you say that white kersies are something fallen of late, butt
sj wooll keeps so high yett they can not fall much till the new wooll comes in
Min & Johan
cij areive will bee now shortley, so I desire you to actt accordinley & if keries fall mored
to goodthen buy 8p. videli et 2 packes each to containe 4 p for each pack maij bee
ijbeinge no lest, then 40 kersies us alsoe 40 bajes in one pack, for m. kent, sende sall
arron hus packes 40 white bayes, when anney double bayes are by, & when all singke
pleft mee
12 baeyes, hee nakes them of 50 ps. so that the 40 ps I ordered is not to much
ban villey for one pack, beside Iam used to have allwayes240 single dosens in one pack
uch lik y ett lett of the 36 single dosens ordered, bee make 3 packes, I hope, wee shall
pose the have a convoij sortley for holland, that I may order you an other assortemen
onttenslics
schienons
for winter, & please to advise from time to time what passel, to take
mj measures accordingley, the convoij is arrived in holland with the ships from
hull, I exspect yd. goods here within 14 dayes, when shall advise you, how
finde tham, m. bollengere hath still about £100:- in handes, dispose there of
pus I wrift you & shall send you more remises p. first, whilst I rest: 16 ditto
gent francois hebrebout
in antwort aonden ul van gisteren de 3 packen No° 5„ 6„ 8 waeren bij ul
gearriveert doch miets de nich vuldige vraght & heet wederconden die niet voor nor ij
gen
te waegen comen & dat het schip van francois maek oock morgen soude vertrocken
des niet tegenstaende soo laet N. 6 88 te waegen comen &N.5 met het schip van
ditto maes, doch oft het gebeurde dat N. 5 p. wagen alreede vertrocken was, soo laet danders oock te
wagen comen & N. 5 op ontfanck deser noch bij ul sijnde doet dat te schepe No 2 moet oock te waegen
comen gue de rest te schepe hope heden & morgen noch eenige paken voor mij heet becomen die gelieft
met ditto maes te lgeten medecomen, dat men saker inste dat maek naeste maendagh hier sou wesen, imen
mdat hij morgens absoliut vertreckt dan te geere N. 6 mede wel te schepe ingesloten, tisschbrief van 4
Amst: geraerds ro ver 36:4 ten latte Janbap:. adelaer waervore dagre ptatie gelieft te besongest oft e steto0 t
sedert mijnen van 13 deser den ul van selven dato ontfangen, godt tel
dat de hulse scheepen binnen sijn, deralven sien mijne packen opt spoedichte
tegemoet als p. mijnen voorgaenden hebbe versocht adroiture so het al soo i
het spoedichste dunckt de wissel op londen is hier tot 35:7 blijven staen
doch miets op de beurs gisteren wederbrieven van 10 sijn aengecomen, soo
waerender op lest tot die prijs veel brieven overgebleven, & miets het
heden h. dagh is soo wort niet getracteert apparent p. naeste wat deling
hope, eenige packen van costij dese weecke sullen vertrecken versocke
advics van wat des wegent passeert & expeditie aen d'ingeslotene blijve
london M: barrensley, powell, & whiting
16 ditto
I have yours of 30 past with a bills of ex. on severall parsons asthere bee
expressed, 3 where of I have sent this day to brussells for acceptance, the others
forgandt & brdges, shall bee sent to morrow, m. bathin is out of town the
bilt lest att this house, as alsoe thatt att the house of m: oudaert, my cosen
Elias is readdy & shall accepted the bill, & you may rest assured of the
monney butt whelst hee hath the monney all ready in cass, so this your great
advantage, that hee should remitt itt, al hee writes to day to you & according
=ley to your answar, hee shall remitt or accept your bils, what futher passes
about the rest shall advise you, & do what tot can to serve you for mij
de ceased frinds sake, the more because mij very goods friend m. Joseph
sabbarton, desires itt alsoe, pray, present mij service to himm & tell him that
I shall tak care to thew you, that is recommandation is aggreable to mee
